# Git Workflow

## Committing — Be Direct

When the user asks to commit (and/or push), go straight to it:

1. `git add -A && git commit -m "message"` (or `--amend --no-edit` for fixes)
2. `git push` (or `--force` for amends)

Do NOT run `git status`, `git diff`, `git log`, or any other exploratory
commands first. You already know what changed because you just made the changes.
Skip the ceremony and just commit.

## Build / CI Fixes

When fixing build failures (lint, formatting, type errors, test failures) caused
by a commit you just made:

1. Fix the issue
2. `git add -A && git commit --amend --no-edit`
3. `git push --force origin develop`

This keeps the history clean — build fixes aren't separate commits.

## New Features / Changes

For new work (features, bug fixes, refactors, doc updates), always create a
**new commit** with a descriptive message. Never amend in this case.

## Rules

- Only amend commits you created in the current session
- Only force push to `develop`, never to `master`
